        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94cd01a0e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>3:3.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Purposes of transfer</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>Transfer of proceedings under this statute is a powerful tool of court administration, and
                        generally an effective tool in bringing about the resolution of complex cases with a minimum
                        burden on the parties and the courts.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The purpose of transfer can be viewed as avoiding “piecemeal litigation.”[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I02391590680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>Transfer under <cite.query w-src-number="0304913951" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                         w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                         ID="I0d883ee0680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407
                    </cite.query> is generally the first step in consolidating or coordinating pretrial activities in
                        numerous actions.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Transfer under this multidistrict venue provision amounts to a change of venue for
                        pretrial purposes.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I0239d8e0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">2</footnote.reference>] The power
                        to transfer is thus both broader and more limited than venue—transfer under the statute is only
                        for pretrial proceedings, not all proceedings, but transfer can be ordered even to districts
                        where venue does not lie.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>This statute, for example, supersedes the general venue statutes[<footnote.reference
                                refid="I0239fff0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>] and special venue
                        statutes.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I0239fff1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">4</footnote.reference>] The power
                        to transfer may supersede the venue provisions of a contract between the parties to the
                        litigation.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I023a9c31680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">5</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        has held that the transfer for pretrial purposes supersedes traditional considerations of
                        “venue,” including the traditional requirement that there be personal jurisdiction over a
                        defendant by the court to which the action is transferred: <?page no="23"?>
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>[D]efendants&apos; argument regarding the
                                unavailability of a single district with jurisdiction over all parties is misdirected.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>Transfer of civil action pursuant to <cite.query w-src-number="0304913951"
                                                                                       w-seq-number="00009"
                                                                                       w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                                                       w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407"
                                                                                       w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                                                       ID="I0d8fb8f0680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">
                                    28 U.S.C. § 1407
                                </cite.query> is for pretrial purposes only and the fact that all parties are not
                                amenable to suit in a particular district does not prevent transfer to that district for
                                pretrial proceedings where the prerequisites of <cite.query w-src-number="0304913951"
                                                                                            w-seq-number="00010"
                                                                                            w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                                                            w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407"
                                                                                            w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                                                            ID="I0d8fb8f1680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">
                                    Section 1407
                                </cite.query> are otherwise satisfied ….
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                Succinctly, venue is not a criterion in deciding the propriety of transfer
                                under <cite.query w-src-number="0304913951" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                  w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                  ID="I0d8fb8f2680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">§ 1407</cite.query>.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I023ac340680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">6</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <paratext>So there.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel&apos;s only function is to determine if transfer is appropriate under the
                        statute; the Panel takes no other or further action in the case.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I023ac341680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">7</footnote.reference>] In
                        practice, the Panel may follow the litigation or be apprised of its progress by the transferee
                        court.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel does not close its files until the cases have been disposed of in the transferee
                        court or remanded to the transferor court.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel has handled cases that have been ongoing for nearly a decade without any formal
                        Panel action.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I023ac342680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">8</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel can order transfer of cases involving different theories, issues, or claims.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>For example, the Panel has ordered transfer of separate securities, antitrust, and
                        declaratory judgment actions for coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I023aea50680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">9</footnote.reference>] Similarly,
                        the Panel can order transfer of antitrust and patent actions for coordinated or consolidated
                        pretrial proceedings,[<footnote.reference refid="I023aea51680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            10</footnote.reference>] and can order transfer of actions involving different parties.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I023b8691680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">11</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        may decline to transfer these different proceedings, but it has the power to order transfer.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>Although the theories and role of transfer is very much on the mind of the Panel, counsel
                        may be focused on more practical effects MDL transfer may have on their cases.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>As one observer has noted:
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>For example, if you are the respondent to a transfer
                                motion or counsel for a party in a ‘tag along’ action (a case subject to transfer by the
                                Panel and consolidation with cases previously transferred and consolidated), the Panel
                                can seize control of your case, thrust you into someone else&apos;s litigation halfway
                                across the country, and relegate you to “100<super>th</super> chair” status in an
                                already over-lawyered mass litigation where coveted ‘lead counsel,’ ‘liaison counsel’
                                and ‘executive committee’ court-appointed case management and <?page no="24"?> litigation leadership
                                positions have already been divvied up.
                                <eos/>
                                <bos/>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I023c70f1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">12</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
